runs.response:
When a user exceeds their query limit the API rejects requests with a 429 (Too Many Requests) and returns rate-limit details. Example responses in the docs:

- Monthly query limit exceeded:
```json
{
  "success": false,
  "error": "Monthly query limit exceeded",
  "usage": {
    "current": 101,
    "max": 100,
    "exceeded": true,
    "reset_at": "2026-02-01T00:00:00Z"
  }
}
```
- Generic rate-limit response:
```json
{
  "error": {
    "code": "RATE_LIMIT_EXCEEDED",
    "message": "Rate limit exceeded. Try again in 60 seconds"
  }
}
```

Responses also include rate-limit headers (X-RateLimit-Limit, X-RateLimit-Remaining, X-RateLimit-Reset) indicating when you can retry. Some limits may instead return an INS UFFICIENT_CREDITS error when credits are exhausted. Recommended handling: check headers, implement exponential backoff, and wait until the reset time.
